        {
          "text": "You are missing one important logic issue in `State.backspace`: the `literal_index` assertion is too strict.\n\nCurrent logic:\n\n```zig\nassert(self.literal_index != null and self.literal_index.? < self.buffer_length);\n```\n\nThat means `backspace()` only works when `literal_index` is set. But based on your intention, backspace should work for ordinary Vietnamese-processing input too, where `literal_index == null`.\n\nExample:\n\n```zig\nvar state: State = undefined;\nlex_state_init(&state);\nstate.mode = .telex;\n\nlex_add(&state, 'a');\nlex_backspace(&state);\n```\n\nExpected: `buffer_length` becomes `0`.\n\nActual with current assertion: panic, because `literal_index == null`.\n\nThe assertion should conceptually mean:\n\n```zig\nliteral_index must be null, or if set, it must be within buffer range.\n```\n\nSo the invariant is:\n\n```zig\nself.literal_index == null or self.literal_index.? < self.buffer_length\n```\n\nnot:\n\n```zig\nself.literal_index != null and self.literal_index.? < self.buffer_length\n```\n\nYour stated logic is otherwise mostly correct:\n\n- Not clearing the actual span is fine because `buffer_length` defines the effective logical length.\n- Clearing `buffer_modification_index` on backspace is reasonable because backspace itself does not retroactively modify an existing span.\n- Unsetting `literal_index` when the new `buffer_length` reaches that index is correct if backspace always removes exactly one character at a time.\n\nThis condition:\n\n```zig\nif (self.literal_index != null and self.literal_index.? == self.buffer_length) {\n    self.literal_index = null;\n}\n```\n\nis okay under the invariant that before backspace:\n\n```zig\nliteral_index < old_buffer_length\n```\n\nAfter decrementing by one, the only way to cross back over `literal_index` is equality.\n\nOne conceptual caveat: your phrase “remove the last span” is only exactly true while `buffer_length <= buffer_effective.len`. When `buffer_length > 16`, there may be no stored `Span` for the last logical character. In that case, backspace removes one logical input position, not necessarily a stored span. Your implementation already reflects that correctly.\n\nSo the main missing logic is: `backspace()` must allow `literal_index == null`.",
